This article discusses President Donald Trump's commemoration of the 18th anniversary of the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks. President Trump and First Lady Melania Trump led a moment of silence with the families of the victims on the White House South Lawn. Later, the President addressed victims' families and members of the Armed Services at the Pentagon. The article also mentions President Trump's visit last year to the Flight 93 National Memorial in Pennsylvania to honor the passengers and crew who fought back against the terrorists. It highlights the sacrifices made by nearly 6 million Americans who have enlisted in the Armed Forces since 9/11, with nearly 7,000 losing their lives. The article emphasizes the importance of educating future generations about the events of 9/11 and the lessons learned from it. President Trump's official Patriot Day Proclamation for 2019 acknowledges America's strength and character in the face of terrorism. Additionally, the article mentions the permanent authorization of the September 11th Victim Compensation Fund, signed into law by President Trump, which provides support to victims, their families, and first responders.